Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are apparently exposed to a smaller risk of getting sick with prostate gland cancer .
That is the surprising result of a study , which was published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer .
That is supposed to be connected with the level of the male hormone testosterone .
Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate gland cancer , particularly in men up to sixty “ , explained the co-author of the study , Ros Eeles , professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick .
The fingers could thus help determine which men should absolutely undergo a prostate gland cancer test , above all , if genetic risks or other factors of risk are present , like for example family health problems , Professor Eeles added .
In the period of 1994-2009 , she monitored more than 1500 patients with prostate gland cancer together with her colleagues in Britain , but at the same time also 3000 healthy men .
In more than half of the participants of the study , the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger .
For these men the same probability of prostate gland cancer exists , as for 19 percent of those men , whose ring and index finger were of equivalent length .
In men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger , however , this risk sank by 33 percent , and in men up to sixty by 87 percent .
